  "text": "Kim and Chung [CITATION_1] conducted a laboratory study of the electromyographic activity of the lower back during dynamic lifting. Eight healthy males participated in four 2-hour trials, lifting and lowering weights between floor and knuckle height. Independent variables were lift type (frequent-lifting, defined as lifting a weight normalized to 10% of the subject's strength six times per minute versus heavy-lifting, defined as lifting a weight normalized to 20% of the subject's strength three times per minute) and posture (symmetric versus 90Њ offset). Muscle activity (normalized EMG) was significantly higher during heavy lifting and during asymmetric lifting (p Ͻ .001). Muscle fatigue during the 2-hour trial (measured by a decrease in the mean power frequency of the EMG signal) was significantly greater during asymmetric and frequent lifting (p Ͻ .001).",
